Graphs showing average value

1.Summary graphs -Plot the mean profiles

Since tracking phenomenon only shows the rise and fall on the data, I couldn’t analysis the data clearly, hence graphs showing average value for each group, and the variation of the observations is important. It is better to study the average instead of each specific data in a huge dataset. I draw a summary graph showing the dataset.

## Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: 'week'.

The summary graph shows the mean of each group in different time. This is clearer than the first two plots, since mean is better to interpret a big dataset (it shows the overall situation clearer). According to the plot, the mean of each group increases as the time pass.

2.Find the Outlier

Outliers might bias for the result, hence, in the next step, I try to find out the outliers and remove them from the dataset.**

According to the boxplot, I find that all the three groups have outlier, hence I filter them out from the dataset, to make the result more unbiased.

** T-test and Anova**

In the last step, I would like to apply t-test to understand the difference between treatment groups, and compute anova.

T test shows that p value is bigger than 0.05, which means that the mean of the two treatment groups aren’t the same. The result can also be seen from sample estimates.(group 1 mean 36.16875, group 2 mean 34.70395) Since baseline measurement of the outcome variable are often correlated with the chosen summary measure in longitudinal study, I add baseline into the dataset, and fit baseline, treatment into linear regression which mean is the response, and run ANOVA. According to the result of ANOVA, baseline is strongly related to the BPRS values.

The Random Intercept Model(The previous model assumes independence of the repeated measures of weight, and this assumption is highly unlikely. So, now we will move on to consider both some more appropriate graphics and appropriate models. To begin the more formal analysis of the rat growth data, we will first fit the random intercept model for the same two explanatory variables: Time and Group. Fitting a random intercept model allows the linear regression fit for each rat to differ in intercept from other rats.We will use the lme4 package which offers efficient tools for fitting linear and generalized linear mixed-effects models. The first argument is the formula object describing both the fixed-effects and random effects part of the model, with the response on the left of a ~ operator and the terms, separated by + operators, on the right. Note the random-effects terms distinguished by vertical bars (|).)

** Slippery slopes: Random Intercept and Random Slope Model (Now we can move on to fit the random intercept and random slope model to the rat growth data. Fitting a random intercept and random slope model allows the linear regression fits for each individual to differ in intercept but also in slope. This way it is possible to account for the individual differences in the rats’ growth profiles, but also the effect of time.)**
